## Origins and Apostolic Succession

The Catholic Church claims to be the one Church founded by Jesus Christ on the Apostle Peter. The foundational text is Matthew 16:18–19, where Jesus says to Peter: "Thou art Peter, and upon this rock I will build my church; and the gates of hell shall not prevail against it. And I will give unto thee the keys of the kingdom of heaven."

Catholics interpret this as Christ founding a Church with Peter as its first head, whose authority passes through an unbroken line of successors — the bishops of Rome (popes). This **apostolic succession** is considered the basis of the Church's authority to administer sacraments and to teach with divine authority.

The **papacy** — the office of the Bishop of Rome as head of the universal Church — developed gradually in the early centuries. Pope Leo I (440–461) was particularly instrumental in establishing the Roman church's primacy in the West, and the First Vatican Council (1869–70) formally defined the doctrine of **papal infallibility**: when the pope speaks *ex cathedra* (from the chair) on matters of faith and morals, binding the whole Church, he is preserved from error.

## The Sacraments

Catholic theology centers on **seven sacraments** — visible, outward rites that convey invisible, inward grace. This sacramental theology, developed especially by Augustine and Aquinas, holds that physical matter can be the vehicle of spiritual grace.

| Sacrament | Purpose | Minister |
|---|---|---|
| Baptism | Removes original sin; initiates into the Church | Any Christian in emergency; normally a priest |
| Eucharist | The real presence of Christ's body and blood | Priest |
| Confirmation | Seals the gift of the Holy Spirit | Bishop |
| Penance (Reconciliation) | Forgiveness of sins committed after baptism | Priest |
| Anointing of the Sick | Spiritual and sometimes physical healing | Priest |
| Holy Orders | Ordination to the diaconate, priesthood, or episcopate | Bishop |
| Matrimony | Grace for Christian marriage | The spouses (priest witnesses) |

### The Eucharist: Transubstantiation

The central sacrament is the **Eucharist** (Mass). At the consecration, the priest pronounces the words of institution ("This is my body... This is my blood"), and Catholic theology holds that the substance of the bread and wine are **transubstantiated** — changed into the actual body and blood of Jesus Christ, while the physical appearances (*accidents*) of bread and wine remain. This doctrine of the **Real Presence** distinguishes Catholic eucharistic theology from most Protestant views.

## Theology and Tradition

Catholic theology rests on two sources of divine revelation:
1. **Scripture:** The entire Bible, including the deuterocanonical books (the "Apocrypha" rejected by Protestants).
2. **Sacred Tradition:** The oral and written tradition of the Church, handed down through apostolic succession and authoritatively interpreted by the Magisterium (the teaching authority of the Church, i.e., the pope and bishops in communion with him).

The **Magisterium** — the Church's official teaching authority — is understood to interpret Scripture and Tradition infallibly in defined matters of faith and morals. This stands in contrast to the Protestant principle of *sola scriptura* (scripture alone).

:::dropdown Major Church Councils
The Catholic Church has held twenty-one **ecumenical councils** — gatherings of bishops from across the world to define doctrine and address crises:

- **Nicaea I (325):** Defined the full divinity of Christ (*homoousios*) against Arianism.
- **Constantinople I (381):** Affirmed the full divinity of the Holy Spirit.
- **Ephesus (431):** Declared Mary *Theotokos* (God-bearer/Mother of God) against Nestorianism.
- **Chalcedon (451):** Defined the two natures (divine and human) of Christ, united in one person.
- **Trent (1545–1563):** Response to the Protestant Reformation; defined Catholic doctrine on Scripture and Tradition, justification, and sacraments.
- **Vatican I (1869–1870):** Defined papal infallibility and primacy.
- **Vatican II (1962–1965):** Pastoral renewal; liturgical reform (Mass in vernacular languages); new approach to ecumenism and religious liberty.
:::

:::dropdown Augustine of Hippo
Saint Augustine (354–430) is arguably the most influential theologian in Western history, shaping both Catholic and Protestant thought. Key doctrines:
- **Original sin:** Adam's sin was inherited by all humanity, corrupting the will and making humans prone to sin.
- **Grace:** Human beings cannot choose the good without divine grace; salvation is entirely God's gift.
- **The City of God:** History is the conflict between the City of God (those predestined to salvation) and the City of Man (those oriented toward earthly goods). The Church is the earthly image of the City of God.

His *Confessions* is one of the greatest spiritual autobiographies ever written.
:::

:::dropdown Thomas Aquinas
Saint Thomas Aquinas (1225–1274) synthesized Aristotle's philosophy with Christian theology in his monumental *Summa Theologica*. His "Five Ways" — five arguments for God's existence — remain the most discussed proofs in philosophy of religion. His theology of natural law, grace, and the sacraments became the standard framework for Catholic theology and was formally endorsed by the Council of Trent and Pope Leo XIII (*Aeterni Patris*, 1879).
:::

## Catholic Moral Teaching

Catholic moral theology draws on natural law (accessible by reason to all humans), divine revelation, and the Church's tradition. Key positions include:
- Opposition to abortion, euthanasia, and embryonic stem-cell research (sanctity of human life from conception)
- Defense of traditional marriage as the union of one man and one woman
- The universal destination of goods (property has a social function)
- Just war theory (moral criteria for the use of military force)
- Care for the poor as a matter of justice, not mere charity

## The Catholic Church and Latter-day Saint Theology

LDS theology identifies the Roman Catholic Church as a sincere inheritor of much that was preserved from the early Church, while also holding that the Great Apostasy resulted in the loss of priesthood authority and the corruption of doctrine. Catholic creeds like the Nicene Creed represent, in LDS view, sincere but misdirected attempts to define God without living prophetic authority. The Restoration was not a critique of Catholic spirituality but a divine intervention to restore what had been lost.

